    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if something like an insect or dirt gets stuck in there, does it usually just cause a slow drift in the reading or is it like a sudden failure? also i heard people call them 'gremlins' when things go wrong with the instruments, but is that just a pilot thing or is there some actual mechanic reason for that term?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When a small obstruction like an insect or dirt gets stuck in the pitot tube, it can cause a gradual drift in the airspeed reading, often referred to as a \"slow creep.\" This can be a subtle issue, and pilots might not even notice it until they start to feel the effects of the inaccurate airspeed reading.\n\nHowever, if the obstruction is larger or more severe, it can cause a sudden failure, where the airspeed reading becomes severely inaccurate or even appears to be reversed. This is often referred to as a \"gremlin\" or \" gremlin event,\" and it's a term that has been used by pilots for decades to describe mysterious and unpredictable failures of aircraft systems.\n\nThe term \"gremlin\" has its roots in World War II, when British pilots began referring to mischievous and troublesome aircraft gremlins that were believed to cause mechanical failures. The term has since been adopted by pilots and aviation enthusiasts to describe any mysterious or unexplained failure of an aircraft system, including the pitot tube.",
      "source": "target",
